04296nam a22005295i 9780226233574DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226233574  a(DE-B1597)524849  a(OCoLC)906576856  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aRK355b.G564 2012eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a617.6322231 aKeighren, Innes M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTravels into Print :bExploration, Writing, and Publishing with John Murray, 1773-1859 /cInnes M. Keighren, Bill Bell, Charles W. J. Withers. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b15 color plates, 25 halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tChapter One. Exploration and Narrative: Travel, Writing, Publishing, and the House of Murray -- tChapter Two. Undertaking Travel and Exploration: Motives and Practicalities -- tChapter Three. Writing the Truth: Claims to Credibility in Exploration and Narrative -- tChapter Four. Explorers Become Authors: Authorship and Authorization -- tChapter Five. Making the Printed Work: Paratextual Material, Visual Images, and Book Production -- tChapter Six. Travel Writing in the Marketplace -- tChapter Seven. Assembling Words and Worlds -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn eighteenth- and nineteenth-century Britain, books of travel and exploration were much more than simply the printed experiences of intrepid authors. They were works of both artistry and industry—products of the complex, and often contested, relationships between authors and editors, publishers and printers. These books captivated the reading public and played a vital role in creating new geographical truths. In an age of global wonder and of expanding empires, there was no publisher more renowned for its travel books than the House of John Murray. Drawing on detailed examination of the John Murray Archive of manuscripts, images, and the firm’s correspondence with its many authors—a list that included such illustrious explorers and scientists as Charles Darwin and Charles Lyell, and literary giants like Jane Austen, Lord Byron, and Sir Walter Scott—Travels into Print considers how journeys of exploration became published accounts and how travelers sought to demonstrate the faithfulness of their written testimony and to secure their personal credibility. This fascinating study in historical geography and book history takes modern readers on a journey into the nature of exploration, the production of authority in published travel narratives, and the creation of geographical authorship—a journey bound together by the unifying force of a world-leading publisher.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGumsxDiseasesxAlternative treatment. 0aGumsxDiseases. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBell, Bill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWithers, Charles W. J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022642953340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226233574423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226233574/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles